metadata.name: Before the storm #4
metadata.description:
"Before the storm" is part of the live minting experience at Non Fungible Conference Lisbon, June 7-8, 2023.

This is a work about the moment when the forces of nature are gathered, but not yet released.
It is about the need for home and shelter, in tension with the need to go outdoors.
It is about stillness and anticipation.
It is about the possibility of emptiness in a world with too many things.
It is about the unsettling closeness of beauty and danger.
It is about climate and the possibility of impending catastrophe.
It is about atmosphere and all that hangs in the air but remains unseen and unsaid.
It is about clouds and complex transient weightless architectures in the sky and the secrets of form without substance.

It is also about the algorithmic simulation of traditional media, like printmaking or ink drawing, and bridging the gap between two ages of art that often look like strangers to each other.

_______________ 

This work is animated. Press ‚ÄúRun‚Äù to see the drawing process.
100% code ‚Äì no assets. Made with p5.js.

Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[r] to restart the drawing
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to download capture
[2] to [9] to generate and save a hi-res image at multiples of the original 800 x 1000 resolution. Please note that rendering at high resolutions can be slow.

(‚ÄúBefore the storm‚Äù is also a tribute to a beautiful and disturbing movie. Can you spot the reference?)

metadata.name: meios #117
Set Disorder #145
metadata.description:
Set Disorder is a work of abstract art using only rectangles and line dashes as brushes, and layered color alpha values as paint. 

The shapes are arranged along a simple grid constrained within one of three aspect ratios; 3:4 / 1:1 / 4:3.

There are 12 color palettes, only one of them is monochrome. üëÄ 

Click or tap on the image to save a png.

made with p5js
@devgenart, 2022

metadata.name: Stranger Flows #95
metadata.description:
The building blocks of Stranger Flows are noise and vectors. Various vector paths create a variety of flows, some continuous, some torn or distorted. Colors are either fully random and mapped with help of noise, or picked from a few select ranges.

There are two modes: light and dark; light mode being slightly less common.

Rendering is animated, once complete pressing 's' in live mode saves a png image.

metadata.name: Drumscapes  #70
metadata.description:
Drumscapes is a fully on-chain generative beat making, landscape creating, audiovisual work by Hexx Audio. 

Each token generates a unique drum beat, which in turn draws a landscape to compliment. There are too many variables in the audio side of things to list as features, so it's safe to say there will never be a repeat beat. No samples are used, all audio is synthesised within the code. BPM alongside variables on the visual side of things make up the features that contribute to rarity. 

Click the canvas to start the audio and watch the sun rise in the east and set in the west.

keyboard tools:
type 'k' to toggle kick drum 
type 's' to toggle snares
type 'h' to toggle hats left
type 'j' to toggle hats right
type 'c' to toggle cowbells
type 'f' to toggle fills 

I hope you enjoy the series. These short loops are ideal for sampling into other music and I'd love to see them used elsewhere.

made with p5.js & tone.js

metadata.name: Gradient Study vol.2 #20
metadata.description:
This is an exploration of gradient algorithms to create a piece of abstract art with harmonic color combinations and compositions. There are several types of patterns and compositions and different color palettes. This artwork is created from hundreds of thousands of points, so rendering it requires quite a lot of CPU and may take some time.

Press ‚Äôs‚Äô on the live mode to save the artwork.

Made with P5js.

metadata.name: lineJag_aliasing #214
metadata.description:
The jaggies created by the lines create smooth noise.
Are they pretending not to notice, or are they really invisible? There is not a single line that is truly loose.
I really want to find evidence that no line is loose.
But I keep finding it and hiding it, then finding it and hiding it.
Still, I feel a little fear and respect for the fact that the straight line connecting "somewhere" and "somewhere" is built on the trust that they are connected, when they are not really connected.
